A Review of Secrets of the Don: Up to Chapter 12

>https://www.sofurry.com/view/1665103
>NameChangedDaily

Overall I really like the story, mainly the interactions between Angelo, Dominic, and Marcy, as well as how Dominic assumes almost a fatherly role over his younger workers.
Overall the praises are numerous, but singing praises isn't what most writers are looking for, so let me put out what seemed off to me.
Firstly, Dominic and Angelo, multiple times Angelo asks Dominic to visit Angelo's family, yet he never does. Wouldn't Angelo hear of this or is it mentioned as a sort of joke, it could make for an interesting interaction for Dominic to go visit the Angelo's family with Marcy and that's how it could be revealed but it doesn't seem that way. Maybe its minor but I did jot it down on "plot holes or other confusing bits of information"
Secondly. In the bowling alley fight scene, why on earth did Dominic let Marcy convince him into fighting the mafia thugs? I can understand why Marcy would speak up about it but she is mentioned to be smart so why would she ask something so suicidal of Dominic. I get rising tension and all that but it just felt jarring as Ramone had not been particularly antagonistic as Dominic knew how he was before hand. It just felt odd, perhaps if the scene at the butchers had ended on a particularly bad note it would've been less so, either way its your decision.

Smiling Tue 10 Aug 2021 20:52:10 No.40812918 Report
Quoted By: >>40816244
>>40812699

Another thing that threw me off was that this was supposed to take place in some *not new york* or just New York, I don't know, I've never been North of the Mason Dixon Line in the U.S for more than a few hours, but back to my point, shouldn't there be more ethnic tension between the American-""Italians""" American-Italians, and just regular Italian rats and more among them from which parts of italy they're from? I've been drinking in German bars and watched some pretty heated arguments between Tuscans, Neapolitans, Lombards, and Sicilians, almost more so than various former Yugoslav "people" and far more than we civilized folk on the Baltic. I think including which part of Italy the neighborhood is from is fairly relevant as it also determines the types of food, just try a Venetian lasagna and compare it to a Lombard one.
You don't have to include stuff about inter italian ethnic tension but its very important to mafia stuff from what I've read.

Lastly, if Dominic is viewed as a traitor by the acting head of the family, why do people treat him with such respect? Even if they respect him wouldn't it be best to ensure they publicly dislike him or at least distrust him? Just something I noticed.

As for the writing itself there are grammatical errors and such but those are mostly irrelevant.

I do very much enjoy the story and figured I'd give it a proper review. As for the strong points: the interpersonal relationships, the general setting, and how Dominic (until the end of chapter 12) tried to hide his past from Marcy and moving forward I am excited to read more, and I should finish the rest by tomorrow

Strong Points:
Setting
General Plot
Cute Waifur
Believable Characters
Actual passage of time

Weak Points
Some Plot Holes
Somewhat unbelievable respect toward Dominic

Overall a very easy story to pick up and read when I had the time and would recommend it to the thread and most folks in general with what I've read so far.
